ACLED

ACLED

The Armed Conflict Location & Event Data (ACLED) project maintains a regularly updated database of violent conflict events and non-violent protests around the globe. Data collection and coding is done by humans and relies on newspaper coverage as well as on social media activity, NGO reports, and other data sets that cover specific regions.

For recent (2010s to the present) activity outside of the US, this is an ideal source for understanding the number, size, or characteristics of large scale protest cycles. However, it may not be a good source if youâre trying to examine a single small or short lived protest movement because you may not have enough detail to conduct quantitative analyses.

Check here for the ACLED codebook, or take a look at some of the recent analyses conducted using ACLED data, or take a look at this recent Washington Post article that uses ACLED data to examine the government crackdown on protests in Myanmar.

Accessing ACLED data

Step 1:

Go to https://developer.acleddata.com/ and register to retrieve an API key.

Step 2:

When you have finished, follow the instructions to login and click the âAdd New Keyâ button at the bottom of the page. Youâll want to copy the key and save it somewhere on your computer for future use.

Step 3:

Now you have two options for accessing data:

  • Either use the Data Export Tool to download data as a .csv file and import it into R

  • Or use the acled.api package to download it from within R. Since option 1 is fairly straightforward, Iâm going to provide instructions on using the ACLED Api here.

Using the ACLED API

First, youâll want to install the acled.api package. Remember that you can install packages by running install.package("packagname"). Once youâve installed a package on your computer, you donât need to install again. However, you will need to import the package every time you reload R if you want to use commands from it. So run library(acled.api) to import the package.

Go ahead and install the usethis package as well, if you donât already have it

# install first
install.packages("acled.api")
# also install usethis if you don't have it already
install.packages("usethis")

Saving your API key in R

The ACLED API package allows you to download data directly from within R, but weâll need to supply our key in order to make the functions work. Since an API key is sort of like a password that you use to authenticate your identity, you donât want to put your key directly in a script. (After all: you want to be able to re-use and share your scripts, and you donât want to have a bunch of sensitive information floating around in them)

Instead, weâll store it as an R environment variable so we can access it later.

If you have the .Renviron installed, you can edit the Renviron by running the code below from within Rstudio

usethis::edit_r_environ()

This will open a new page called .Renviron.

Youâll want to write the following lines to this file (swapping in your own API key and email address):

ACLED_API_KEY = 'YOUR API KEY in quotes'
ACLED_EMAIL = 'the email you used to register in quotes'

Finally, click ctrl + s to save the file, and then restart R-studio. When youâve done this, you should be able to access those environment variables from Rstudio by running something like Sys.getenv('variable_name_here'). For instance:

Sys.getenv("ACLED_EMAIL")
[1] "nlund@umd.edu"
# Or Sys.getenv("ACLED_API_KEY") to access the key

So you can use these commands to send your API key from within R without having to actually write your password into an R script.

Sending an API request

Now that you have your API Key and email stored in R, you should be able to send requests to the ACLED API. Weâll send a request that finds all incidents of state forces using violence against peaceful protesters since the start of 2024:

# load the acled.api library:
library(acled.api)
oct_events<-acled.api(
  email.address = Sys.getenv("ACLED_EMAIL"),
  access.key = Sys.getenv("ACLED_API_KEY"),
  start.date = "2024-10-01",
  end.date ="2024-10-17",                      
  all.variables = TRUE
)
1
Adding the access key and email address as environment variables (this avoids putting my api key directly in the Rscript)
2
We can (optionally) set a specific start and end date to retrieve. If I left these commands out, I would retrieve everything, but thatâs probably not a good idea because thereâs a ton of ACLED data.
3
By default, this command only returns a subset of the available columns, all.variables=TRUE ensures we get all of the stuff that ACLED codes about an event.

Something to keep in mind: when you run this command, youâre sending a request to the servers maintained by the people who run ACLED. Theyâre probably set up to handle a lot of traffic, but you want to be careful about requesting too much too frequently. So you probably should save your results if you intend to re-use this data.

You can store your results in a .csv file like this:

readr::write_csv(oct_events, "oct_2024_events.csv")
# re-open it by running:
# oct_events <- readr::read_csv("oct_2024_events.csv")

Alternatively, you could store them in a .rds file (which can only be read by R) like this:

saveRDS(oct_events, "oct_2024_events.rds")
# re-open it by running:
# oct_events<-readRDS("oct_2024_events.rds")

Once all is said and done, I would recommend writing the code you used to download and save results all together in one script and saving it separately from the script youâll be using for your analyses. The final script would look like this:

# load the acled.api library:
library(acled.api)
oct_events<-acled.api(
  email.address = Sys.getenv("ACLED_EMAIL"),
  access.key = Sys.getenv("ACLED_API_KEY"),
  start.date = "2024-10-01",
  end.date ="2024-10-17",
  all.variables = TRUE
)

readr::write_csv(oct_events, "oct_2024_events.csv")

Analyzing the data

Lets go ahead and dig into that October event data again. Remember that you can load a previously saved CSV with the read_csv command:

library(tidyverse)
oct_events  <- read_csv("oct_2024_events.csv")

ACLED data is not limited to protest activity! They include multiple different kinds of contentious interactions. The general âtypeâ of event is recorded in the event_type variable. Remember that you can get counts of a categorical variable using the count function, so we can get a sense of the different event types like this:

oct_events|> 
  count(event_type)

Making a barplot

One thing we might want to do with this result is create a barplot that shows the number of instances of violence against civilians in each country for the relevant time frame. We can use ggplot to generate this.

Start by filtering by event type to grab only the relevant events:

violence<-country_counts|>
  filter(event_type=='Violence against civilians')

Then set up our empty plotting space using the ggplot function:

viol_plot <- ggplot(violence, aes(x=country, y=n))

Enter âviol_plotâ into the console to see what this looks like so far:

viol_plot

You might notice an issue here already! The axis labels are overlapping. We could fix this by creating a really big plotting space, but an easier solution might be to just flip the x and y axis here. We can flip the axes of an existing plot with the coord_flip function:

viol_plot<-viol_plot + 
  coord_flip()

Enter viol_plot in the console to see what this looks like now. You should see something like this:

(you might still need to adjust the size of the plotting window to get the axis labels to stop overlapping)

Now that we have our plot set up, we will want to add the bars themselves. We can add a bar with the geom_bar() function. (geom_bar can produce other summary statistics, so we use stat="identity" here because we want the height of each bar to be based on the value of n.)

viol_plot <- viol_plot + geom_bar(stat='identity')

This is much closer! Now a couple of things we might want to modify here. I want to add axis labels, a title, and a caption, and also change the color scheme to a simple black-and-white instead of the greyscale default. I can do that like this:

viol_plot <- viol_plot +
  # x axis label
  xlab("Country") +
  # y axis label
  ylab("Number of events") +
  # title and caption
  labs(title = "Incidents of violence against civilians in October 2024",
              caption = "Data source: ACLED") +
  # black-and-white theme
  theme_bw()

Once Iâm satisfied with my output, I might want to be able to show my result in a Word document. I can actually copy-paste directly from the output window, but this can sometimes result in really low-resolution plots. A better option is to save the plot using ggsave and then import it into a word document.

You can use the width and height arguments to adjust the sizing of your plot. Usually this will require some guessing and checking to get right, but you want to aim for a size that avoids cutting off any relevant information.

ggsave(viol_plot, filename='october_violence.png', width=10, height=8, units='in')

Once you have a saved plot, you can import it into a Word document by going to Insert -> Pictures -> Insert picture from this device and then importing the file you just created.

Making it in one step

We did this in multiple steps so we could see how the changes impacted our output, but we can create this entire barplot with one long block of code. Hereâs what it looks like when we just put everything together:

  • Original
  • Ordered by frequency
  • Ordered by frequency with a different fill color
viol_plot <- ggplot(violence, aes(x = country, y = n)) +
  # make it horizontal
  coord_flip() +
  # add the bars
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity') +
  # x axis label
  xlab("Country") +
  # y axis label
  ylab("Number of events") +
  # title and caption
  labs(title = "Incidents of violence against civilians in October 2024",
              caption = "Data source: ACLED") +
  # black-and-white theme
  theme_bw()

The default setting here sorts these results alphabetically, but we can use the reorder function to sort a vector by some other characteristic. Here, Iâm making the same plot but ordering based on the value of n:

viol_plot <- ggplot(violence, aes(x = reorder(country, n), y = n)) +
  # make it horizontal
  coord_flip() +

Bringing in the V-DEM data

We can use data from the V-DEM institute for characteristics of different countries. Thereâs an R-package to download data the latest data from VDEM, which you can install with the following command:

devtools::install_github("vdeminstitute/vdemdata")

Once youâve installed it, you can import the VDEM data like this:

vdem<-vdemdata::vdem

Take a minute to examine some of the variables and the codebook, identify the unit of analysis, and try to get a sense of what sorts of options are available for thinking about the nature of a countryâs government.

Plotting recent democracy scores

VDEM has what we would call âcross sectional time seriesâ data: it contains data on multiple countries over multiple years. This can be helpful if weâre trying to look at a relationship over time, but in some cases we might just be interested in the most recent data. VDEM actually has coverage through 2023, but weâre going to pull 2018 here instead because some of the variables only go through that date:

vdem_recent<-vdem|>
  filter(year == 2018)

Histogram of democracy

We can make a simple histogram to show the distribution of a single continuous variable. The code for this is simple. We only need to specify an âxâ variable and then use the geom_histogram function:

ggplot(vdem_recent, aes(x=v2x_libdem)) + 
  geom_histogram()

Bar plot of democracy

We can use another bar plot to look at one of the democracy score variables in this dataset. Weâll also use the reorder function to sort the countries from the highest democracy score to the lowest:

ggplot(vdem_recent, aes(x=reorder(country_name, v2x_libdem), y=v2x_libdem)) + 
  geom_bar(stat='identity')+
  coord_flip() +
  theme_bw() +
  ylab('Liberal Democracy score') +
  xlab("Country") + 
  labs(title = "Countries by Liberal Democracy Score",
              caption = "Data source: VDEM")

Democracy and GDP

VDEM has a variable for GDP per capita through 2018. We can use this to get a sense of the relationship between liberal democracy and wealth. The basic setup here will be very similar to the setup we used to make a bar plot: we need a data set, an x-axis variable, and a y-axis variable, but instead of using geom_bar we can use geom_scatter

ggplot(vdem_recent, aes(x=e_gdppc, y=v2x_libdem)) + 
  geom_point() +
  theme_bw() +
  xlab('GDP Per-Capita') +
  ylab("Liberal-Democracy score") + 
  labs(title = "GDP by Liberal Democracy Score",
              caption = "Data source: VDEM")
